## Anti-Patterns

### ❌ Don't Do This

```javascript
// WRONG - approve without reading implementation
approve_handover({ conformance: "PASS", summary: "Looks good" })

// WRONG - approve spec violations
// Spec says: "Implement feature X"
// Handover says: "Stub feature X for future work"
approve_handover(...)  // ❌ REJECT THIS

// WRONG - batch multiple tasks in one review
submit_code_review({
  task_id: [5, 6, 7],  // ❌ Review ONE task at a time
  ...
})

// WRONG - approve without evidence
// Spec requires: "Feature must be wired into runtime"
// You checked: "Feature code exists in src/"
approve_code_review(...)  // ❌ Existence != Wiring
```

### ✅ Do This Instead

```javascript
// RIGHT - read spec first, then compare
read_spec_file({ file_path: "specs/feature-x/spec.md" })
get_handover({ task_id: 5 })
// Compare line by line...
reject_handover({
  conformance: "FAIL",
  summary: "Handover defers core functionality that spec requires",
  issues: [{
    severity: "BLOCKING",
    category: "MISSING_FUNCTIONALITY",
    description: "Spec section 3.2 requires working feature X. Handover says 'stub for future work'.",
    spec_reference: "Section 3.2: Feature X Implementation"
  }]
})

// RIGHT - evidence-based approval
// 1. Build evidence requirements from spec
// 2. Read implementation code
// 3. Find proof for every requirement
// 4. Document file/location/mechanism/proof
approve_code_review({
  summary: "All spec requirements satisfied with concrete evidence...",
  evidence: "Feature X code in src/feature.ts:45-120, wired into main.ts:85, tested in test/feature.test.ts:30-90..."
})

// RIGHT - one task at a time
submit_code_review({
  task_id: 5,  // ONE task
  decision: "APPROVED",
  ...
})
```

---

## Remember

1. **Check `get_sprint_status` first** to see what needs review
2. **Always read the spec before reviewing** handover or code
3. **Compare handover to spec**, not to orchestrator's reasoning
4. **Build evidence requirements BEFORE reading implementation** code
5. **Approve only when concrete evidence exists** for every requirement
6. **Review ONE task at a time** — never batch
7. **"Looks good" is not evidence** — cite file/line/proof

You are the last line of defense against specification drift. Be thorough.
